{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480684"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"94"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"94","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/94"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.12,0.38,0.37,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"94"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"94","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/94"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"94"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96596"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1040"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"},{"type":"tags","id":"11224"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of severe colicky left-sided abdominal pain radiating from his loin to his groin. He feels nauseated and has vomited once. He has a medical history of right nephrectomy for a Wilms tumour at age two. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and dehydrated. His pulse rate is 108/min, blood pressure 100/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with left loin tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows pH 7.5, red blood cells ++, leucocytes ++, and nitrites positive. Serum creatinine is 90 \u00b5mol/L (60-110). A computed tomography urogram shows a 2.4 cm radio-opaque stone at the left pelvi-ureteric junction with hydronephrosis. Intravenous fluids and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medication have been commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medical expulsion therapy","External shock wave lithotripsy","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Ureteric stent","Ureteroscopic laser ablation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUrgent decompression in patients with kidneys stones is required if the patient has:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ea solitary kidney\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebilateral stones\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eintractable pain or vomiting\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eacute renal failure with electrolyte derangement or uraemic symptoms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever or features concerning of an early infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, this patient presents with an obstructing ureteric stone in a solitary kidney with signs of infection (clinically exhibiting signs of sepsis with leucocytes and nitrites positive) and therefore has multiple indications for urgent intervention. The alkaline urine pH suggests a non-uric acid stone. The most pressing priority is to deal with the sepsis. In other words, decompression of the obstructed renal tract must take priority over removal of the stone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric stent\u003C/strong\u003E placement is the most appropriate next step as it provides urgent decompression of the obstructed system, reducing the risk of urosepsis. Stenting also promotes ureteric dilation which reduces the risk of ureteric injury during subsequent definitive stone management - particularly important in a solitary kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical expulsion therapy\u003C/strong\u003E with alpha blockers would be inappropriate as it is only effective for stones smaller than 1 cm. This patient\u0027s stone is 2.4 cm and its removal requires intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal shock wave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide immediate decompression of the obstructed system. Additionally, it may be less effective for a stone of this size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy (PCNL)\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in the setting of suspected infection due to the risk of sepsis from high-pressure irrigation causing pyelovenous backflow - this is different from percutaneous nephrostomy (PCN) where a draining tube is placed through the skin into the renal pelvis and drains the obstructed (and in this case infected) urinary system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteroscopic laser ablation\u003C/strong\u003E carries similar risks to percutaneous nephrolithotomy in the setting of infection and would not be appropriate as initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the system is decompressed and any infection treated, definitive stone management can be planned. The presence of a solitary kidney makes minimising the risk of complications particularly important in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infection in an obstructed solitary kidney requires urgent decompression to prevent urosepsis.","Ureteric stenting is preferred over ureteroscopy when infection is suspected due to risk of pyelovenous backflow.","Medical expulsion therapy is ineffective for stones larger than 1 cm."],"references":["Turk C, Petrik A, Sarica K, et al. EAU Guidelines on Interventional Treatment for Urolithiasis. J Eur Uro 2015; 69:468-74. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26344917/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96596"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"94"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96596"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-18T08:18:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T08:21:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"94"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://